1. Change Password
bashpasswd
# You'll be prompted to enter your current password, then the new one twice

2. Display System Date
bashdate
Output: Wed May 20 02:26:59 UTC 2026

3. Count Lines in /etc/passwd
bashwc -l /etc/passwd
Output: 23 /etc/passwd

4. Find Who Else is on the System
bashwho
# or
w
Lists all currently logged-in users with terminal and login time.

5. Redirect man page of date to file mydate
bashman date | col -b > mydate
# col -b strips formatting/backspaces for clean output
Result: mydate created with 110 lines.

6. Create Subdirectory mydir
bashmkdir mydir

7. Move mydate into mydir
bashmv mydate mydir/

8. Go to mydir and Copy mydate to ourdate
bashcd mydir
cp mydate ourdate

9. List Contents of mydir
bashls mydir/
Output: mydate  ourdate

10. Long Listing of ourdate — Note Permissions
bashls -l mydir/ourdate
Output: -rw-r--r-- 1 root root 0 May 20 02:26 mydir/ourdate
Permissions: owner can read+write; group and others can only read.

11. Display Current Directory from Root
bashpwd
Output: /home/claude

12. Move Files from mydir Back to Home
bashmv mydir/* ~/

13. Display First 5 Lines of mydate
bashhead -5 mydate
Usage: date [OPTION]... [+FORMAT]
  or:  date [-u|--utc|--universal] [MMDDhhmm[[CC]YY][.ss]]
Display date and time in the given FORMAT.
With -s, or with [MMDDhhmm[[CC]YY][.ss]], set the date and time.

14. Display Last 8 Lines of mydate
bashtail -8 mydate

15. Remove Directory mydir
bashrmdir mydir

16. Redirect Long Listing to File list
bashls -l > list

17. Create capitals1, capitals2, capitals3 → Concatenate to capitals
bash# capitals1 — Maharashtra cities
printf "Mumbai\nPune\nNagpur\nNashik\nAurangabad\n" > capitals1

# capitals2 — South India cities
printf "Chennai\nHyderabad\nBengaluru\nKochi\nTrivandrum\n" > capitals2

# capitals3 — East/Central India cities
printf "Kolkata\nPatna\nBhopal\nJaipur\nLucknow\n" > capitals3

# Concatenate all 3
cat capitals1 capitals2 capitals3 > capitals

18. Append capitals2 to End of capitals
bashcat capitals2 >> capitals

19. Give Read+Write Permissions to All Users for capitals
bashchmod a+rw capitals
Result: -rw-rw-rw-

20. Give Read-Only Permission to Owner
bashchmod u=r,go-rw capitals
ls -l capitals   # → -r--------
Now open the file in vi/nano and try to save — you'll get "Permission denied" because even the owner has no write permission. The file is read-only.

21. Create Alias to Concatenate capitals1+2+3
bashalias makeCapitals='cat capitals1 capitals2 capitals3 > capitals'

# Activate and run it:
makeCapitals
To make it permanent, add it to ~/.bashrc.

22. Count Occurrences of "the" in mydate
bashgrep -oi '\bthe\b' mydate | wc -l
Output: 22

23. Line Numbers Where "date" Exists in mydate
bashgrep -n "date" mydate
